line_1: To you, dear sir, my best regards I send,
line_2: The weakest reasoner, as the truest friend.

line_1: Your arts, your country, and your palaces;

line_1: What signs of Roman grandeur still remain —
line_2: Much you have said; and much have said in vain.

line_1: Much you have said; and much have said in vain.

line_1: Fine pageants these for slaves, to please the eye;
line_2: And put the neatest dress on misery!

line_1: And put the neatest dress on misery!

line_1: Bred up to slav'ry and dissembled pain,
line_2: Unhappy man! you trifle with your chain:

line_1: Unhappy man! you trifle with your chain:

line_1: But should your friend with your desires comply,
line_2: And sell himself to Rome and slav'ry;

line_1: You'd soon repent the livery that you gave;
line_2: For, trust me, I should make an aukward slave.

line_1: For, trust me, I should make an aukward slave.

line_1: Early in hardships through the woods they fly,
line_2: Nor feel the piercing frost, or wintry sky;

line_1: Nor feel the piercing frost, or wintry sky;
line_2: Early in hardships through the woods they fly,

line_1: Some prowling wolf or foamy boar to meet,
line_2: And stretch the panting savage at their feet:

line_1: And stretch the panting savage at their feet:

line_1: Inur'd by this, they seek a nobler war,
line_2: And show an honest pride in ev'ry scar;

line_1: And show an honest pride in ev'ry scar;
line_2: Inur'd by this, they seek a nobler war,

line_1: With joy the danger and the blood partake,
line_2: Whilst ev'ry wound is for their country's sake.

line_1: Whilst ev'ry wound is for their country's sake.

line_1: Or faintly strike, or impotently yield;

line_1: For well this universal truth you know,
line_2: Who fights for tyrants is his country's foe.

line_1: Who fights for tyrants is his country's foe.

line_1: I envy not your arts, the Roman schools,
line_2: Improv'd, perhaps, but to inslave your souls.

line_1: Improv'd, perhaps, but to inslave your souls.
line_2: I envy not your arts, the Roman schools,

line_1: May you to stone, or nerves or beauty give,
line_2: And teach the soft'ning marble how to live;

line_1: And teach the soft'ning marble how to live;
line_2: May you to stone, or nerves or beauty give,

line_1: May you the passions in your colours trace,
line_2: And work up every piece with every grace;

line_1: And work up every piece with every grace;
line_2: May you the passions in your colours trace,

line_1: In airs and attitudes be wondrous wise,
line_2: And know the arts to please, or to surprize;

line_1: And know the arts to please, or to surprize;
line_2: In airs and attitudes be wondrous wise,

line_1: In musick's softest sound consume the day,
line_2: Sounds that would melt the warrior's soul away:

line_1: Sounds that would melt the warrior's soul away:
line_2: In musick's softest sound consume the day,

line_1: Vain efforts these, an honest fame to raise;
line_2: Your painters, and your eunuchs, be your praise:

line_1: Your painters, and your eunuchs, be your praise:
line_2: Vain efforts these, an honest fame to raise;

line_1: Grant us more real goods, you heav'nly powers!
line_2: Virtue, and arms, and liberty be ours.

line_1: Virtue, and arms, and liberty be ours.
line_2: Grant us more real goods, you heav'nly powers!

line_1: Weak are your offers to the free and brave;
line_2: No bribe can purchase me to be a slave.

line_1: No bribe can purchase me to be a slave.
line_2: Weak are your offers to the free and brave;

line_1: Hear me, ye rocks, ye mountains, and ye plains,
line_2: The happy bounds of our Helvetian swains!

line_1: The happy bounds of our Helvetian swains!
line_2: Hear me, ye rocks, ye mountains, and ye plains,

line_1: In thee, my country, will I fix my seat;
line_2: Nor envy the poor wretch, that would be great:

line_1: Nor envy the poor wretch, that would be great:
line_2: In thee, my country, will I fix my seat;

line_1: My life and arms I dedicate to thee; —
line_2: For, know, it is my int'rest to be free.

line_1: For, know, it is my int'rest to be free.
